{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b835c014-e933-4a38-aeef-284c763a25b0","content":"Yes, your tutorial's advice is **correct and current for .NET MAUI on .NET 10**.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This is the right approach. Add the iOS platform-specific namespace and set it on your `ContentPage`:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nThis shifts your page content to avoid the notch, status bar, and home indicator.\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Also correct. Use it on a layout (like `Grid`) to let a background image extend *into* the safe area while the rest of the page respects it:\n\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\nBoth APIs are stable parts of .NET MAUI and remain the recommended approach. The two work well together — `UseSafeArea` protects your interactive content, while `IgnoreSafeArea` on a specific container lets decorative elements bleed edge-to-edge.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e30aea5-5bc1-4bfa-9b8e-97603a202397","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me search for information about these APIs in the current repository context, and also check what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs.\n\nFrom my knowledge:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - This was the approach in earlier versions of .NET MAUI / Xamarin.Forms. \n\nFor the first property, I need to use the iOS-specific namespace with the proper XAML declaration to access `Page.UseSafeArea`, which controls whether content respects the safe area boundaries on iOS devices. For the second property, `IgnoreSafeArea` on layouts like Grid lets content extend beyond the safe area, which is useful for full-bleed background images. layouts like Grid can extend into the safe area, which is useful for background images. Both approaches are valid .NET MAUI APIs, though I should note I don't have specific information about whether these have changed in .NET 10. The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property requires the iOS-specific namespace to work properly and tells the page to respect the safe area boundaries.","outputTokens":1115,"requestId":"1014:1E9A5D:15E5EDA:189BAD3:69FD37A2"},"id":"269a22f0-0574-43e6-a728-194866f13d5a","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:09:13.726Z","parentId":"9487d3ce-8e79-40b1-acc7-59cae77df9f7"}
